#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:404
msgid "Matrix objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:410
msgid ""
"It is strongly advised *not* to use the matrix subclass.  As described "
"below, it makes writing functions that deal consistently with matrices and "
"regular arrays very difficult. Currently, they are mainly used for "
"interacting with ``scipy.sparse``. We hope to provide an alternative for "
"this use, however, and eventually remove the ``matrix`` subclass."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:416
msgid ""
":class:`matrix` objects inherit from the ndarray and therefore, they have "
"the same attributes and methods of ndarrays. There are six important "
"differences of matrix objects, however, that may lead to unexpected results "
"when you use matrices but expect them to act like arrays:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:422
msgid ""
"Matrix objects can be created using a string notation to allow Matlab-style "
"syntax where spaces separate columns and semicolons (';') separate rows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:426
msgid ""
"Matrix objects are always two-dimensional. This has far-reaching "
"implications, in that m.ravel() is still two-dimensional (with a 1 in the "
"first dimension) and item selection returns two-dimensional objects so that "
"sequence behavior is fundamentally different than arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:432
msgid ""
"Matrix objects over-ride multiplication to be matrix-multiplication. **Make "
"sure you understand this for functions that you may want to receive "
"matrices. Especially in light of the fact that asanyarray(m) returns a "
"matrix when m is a matrix.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:438
msgid ""
"Matrix objects over-ride power to be matrix raised to a power. The same "
"warning about using power inside a function that uses asanyarray(...) to get "
"an array object holds for this fact."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:442
msgid ""
"The default __array_priority\\__ of matrix objects is 10.0, and therefore "
"mixed operations with ndarrays always produce matrices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:445
msgid ""
"Matrices have special attributes which make calculations easier. These are"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:455:<autosummary>:1
msgid ":py:obj:`matrix.T <numpy.matrix.T>`\\"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:455:<autosummary>:1
msgid "Returns the transpose of the matrix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:455:<autosummary>:1
msgid ":py:obj:`matrix.H <numpy.matrix.H>`\\"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:455:<autosummary>:1
msgid "Returns the (complex) conjugate transpose of `self`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:455:<autosummary>:1
msgid ":py:obj:`matrix.I <numpy.matrix.I>`\\"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:455:<autosummary>:1
msgid "Returns the (multiplicative) inverse of invertible `self`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:455:<autosummary>:1
msgid ":py:obj:`matrix.A <numpy.matrix.A>`\\"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:455:<autosummary>:1
msgid "Return `self` as an `ndarray` object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:458
msgid ""
"Matrix objects over-ride multiplication, '*', and power, '**', to be matrix-"
"multiplication and matrix power, respectively. If your subroutine can accept "
"sub-classes and you do not convert to base- class arrays, then you must use "
"the ufuncs multiply and power to be sure that you are performing the correct "
"operation for all inputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:465
msgid ""
"The matrix class is a Python subclass of the ndarray and can be used as a "
"reference for how to construct your own subclass of the ndarray. Matrices "
"can be created from other matrices, strings, and anything else that can be "
"converted to an ``ndarray`` . The name \"mat \"is an alias for \"matrix \"in "
"NumPy."
msgstr ""

