#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:632
msgid "Standard container class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:636
msgid ""
"For backward compatibility and as a standard \"container \"class, the "
"UserArray from Numeric has been brought over to NumPy and named :class:"
"`numpy.lib.user_array.container` The container class is a Python class whose "
"self.array attribute is an ndarray. Multiple inheritance is probably easier "
"with numpy.lib.user_array.container than with the ndarray itself and so it "
"is included by default. It is not documented here beyond mentioning its "
"existence because you are encouraged to use the ndarray class directly if "
"you can."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:649:<autosummary>:1
msgid ""
":py:obj:`numpy.lib.user_array.container <numpy.lib.user_array.container>`\\ "
"\\(data\\[\\, ...\\]\\)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:649:<autosummary>:1
msgid "Standard container-class for easy multiple-inheritance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:656
msgid "Array iterators"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:663
msgid ""
"Iterators are a powerful concept for array processing. Essentially, "
"iterators implement a generalized for-loop. If *myiter* is an iterator "
"object, then the Python code::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:667
msgid ""
"for val in myiter:\n"
"    ...\n"
"    some code involving val\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:672
msgid ""
"calls ``val = next(myiter)`` repeatedly until :exc:`StopIteration` is raised "
"by the iterator. There are several ways to iterate over an array that may be "
"useful: default iteration, flat iteration, and :math:`N`-dimensional "
"enumeration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:679
msgid "Default iteration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:681
msgid ""
"The default iterator of an ndarray object is the default Python iterator of "
"a sequence type. Thus, when the array object itself is used as an iterator. "
"The default behavior is equivalent to::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:685
msgid ""
"for i in range(arr.shape[0]):\n"
"    val = arr[i]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.classes.rst:688
msgid ""
"This default iterator selects a sub-array of dimension :math:`N-1` from the "
"array. This can be a useful construct for defining recursive algorithms. To "
"loop over the entire array requires :math:`N` for-loops."
msgstr ""

